data.content:
Here's the complete migration. Your code has three `Thread.Abort`-dependent patterns that don't exist in ASP.NET Core:

| .NET Framework Pattern | Problem in .NET 8 | ASP.NET Core Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Just return from the action |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `endResponse=true` calls `Thread.Abort` | Return `Redirect()` result |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown in modern .NET | Remove entirely |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // ASP.NET Core: return IActionResult instead of void event handlers.
    // The framework handles the response lifecycle — no need to Clear/End.
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // FileContentResult sets headers and writes the body in one shot.
        // No Response.Clear(), Write(), or End() needed.
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv");
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Redirect()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Just return a RedirectResult — no Thread.Abort, no endResponse.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // ThreadAbortException catch is removed entirely:
        // - ASP.NET Core never throws it
        // - Response.Redirect no longer aborts the thread
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls to Watch For

**1. Don't write to `Response` then return a result — pick one.**
```csharp
// WRONG — mixing both throws InvalidOperationException
Response.WriteAsync("data");
return File(bytes, "text/csv");

// RIGHT — use the result object exclusively
return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
```

**2. `User.Identity` can be `null` in ASP.NET Core.**
The original `User.Identity.IsAuthenticated` will `NullReferenceException` if no auth middleware is configured. Use null-conditional: `User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? false`.

**3. Don't catch `OperationCanceledException` and swallow it.**
ASP.NET Core uses `HttpContext.RequestAborted` for client disconnects. If you have long-running work, pass the token through:
```csharp
[HttpPost]
public async Task<IActionResult> Export(CancellationToken cancellationToken)
{
    // Framework injects HttpContext.RequestAborted automatically
    var data = await GenerateReportAsync(cancellationToken);
    return File(Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data), "text/csv", "report.csv");
}
```

**4. Event handlers → Action methods.** ASP.NET Core has no `btnExport_Click` postback model. Each action is a routed endpoint returning `IActionResult`. Make sure your routing is configured:
```csharp
// Program.cs
app.MapControllerRoute(
    name: "default",
    pattern: "{controller=Home}/{action=Index}/{id?}");
```

**5. No `Response.Clear()` equivalent is needed.** ASP.NET Core doesn't buffer a partial response that needs clearing — the response starts clean.

## Summary of Removed APIs

| Removed | Replacement | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.Clear()` | Remove | Response is clean by default |
| `Response.Write(data)` | `return File(...)` | Let the framework write the response |
| `Response.End()` | `return` | Just return from the action |
| `Response.AddHeader(...)` | Handled by `File()` result | Result objects set headers automatically |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `return Redirect(url)` | No thread abort, no `endResponse` param |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Remove | Never thrown in .NET 8 |
